Now I can see the bug. On line 95:

```js
const waitSeconds = retryAfter ? parseInt(retryAfter, 10) || delay : delay;
```

When `Retry-After: "0"`:
- `retryAfter` is `"0"` (non-empty string, truthy)
- `parseInt("0", 10)` returns `0` which is falsy
- So `parseInt("0", 10) || delay` evaluates to `delay` (the default delay), not `0`

The fix: replace the truthiness check with an explicit null check and isNaN check.

```js
const waitSeconds = retryAfter !== null && !isNaN(parseInt(retryAfter, 10)) ? parseInt(retryAfter, 10) : delay;
```

Or more simply:
```js
const retryAfterSeconds = retryAfter !== null ? parseInt(retryAfter, 10) : NaN;
const waitSeconds = !isNaN(retryAfterSeconds) ? retryAfterSeconds : delay;
```

